{[%evp 0,18,18,-13,-13,-13,-11,-23,12,12,5,1,25,-47,8,0,0,7,51,57,54] Hello
and welcome to my first-ever course for Modern Chess! In this course, we will
be examining 1.c4 e5 from Black. The objective of this course is to present a
dynamic and fresh repertoire against the English. Players who usually English
are looking for a positional game, so from a philosophical point of view,
entering sharp & complex positions makes a lot of sense.} 1. c4 e5 {The
starting point of our repertoire. We will be going through all of White's
major alternatives from this position. Let me introduce you to the two major
systems for White here.} 2. Nc3 {The first of the two major systems. White
develops a knight, and increases control over the d5-square. The advantage of
this system is that White can be a bit more flexible unlike 2.g3, where White
has to commit the bishop to the g2-square.} (2. g3 {The second major system
for White. He wants to put the bishop on g2, where it is most actively placed.
However, there are a couple of strategic drawbacks to this move. Firstly,
White isn't actively fighting for center. Secondly, the pawn on g3 can be a
hook which we can try to exploit with} h5 $5 {a very interesting & fresh
practical try. We are anticipating Bg2, which we intend to meet by playing h4.
These positions are very dynamic and complex, and not easy for your opponent
to play without knowing.} ({If you are looking for an alternative,} 2... f5 $5
3. Bg2 Nc6 {is very similar, and may transpose to our repertoire against 2.Nc3
in many situations. This can be a great alternative for you, if you are
worried about playing 2...h5 repeatatively.}) {Let me take you through some of
White's options here.} 3. Nf3 {The best move according to the computer. White
develops a piece and stops h4.} ({the natural} 3. Bg2 {runs into} h4 {[%csl
Rg2][%cal Gh4h3,Gd7d6,Yh4g3] giving Black great practical chances. We are
looking to play d6-h3 next, posing uncomfortable questions to the g2-bishop,
or hxg3, depending upon the situation.}) ({against the prophylactic} 3. h3 {
, I recommend going} d5 {[%csl Rh3][%cal Gc8h3] which is a better version of
the traditional 2.g3 d5 lines, as our bishop on c8 has sights on the h3-pawn.})
({against the natural} 3. Nc3 {I recommend going} h4 4. g4 d5 $5 {which leads
to some unconventional and complex positions.}) 3... e4 {We gain space in the
center, and challenge White's knight} 4. Nh4 {This unorthodox and rather
difficult move is White's best bet for an advantage.} ({The natural} 4. Nd4 {
can be easily parried away with} Nc6 5. Nxc6 dxc6 {[%csl Rc1,Ge4][%cal Gh5h4]
Where Black already takes over the initiative due to the extra space in the
center, and the threat of h5-h4.}) {here, I recommend} 4... Be7 {developing a
piece and threatening to win a pawn.} 5. Nf5 {White's most natural move in the
position is} ({Another interesting line for White is} 5. Nc3 {intending to
meet Bxh4 with gxh4 Qxh4 d3. White keeps an edge there due to better pieces
and pair of bishops. Instead, I recommend} c6 $5 {With sharp play.}) {I
propose going} 5... d6 6. Nxe7 Qxe7 {[%cal Gb8c6,Gc8f5,Gg8f6] where the
position is still sharp, but Black retains natural and intuitive moves.}) 2...
Nc6 {[%csl Rd4,Ge5,Gf5,Gg6][%cal Yc6d4,Gd2d4,Gf7f5,Gg7g6,Gf8g7,Gd7d6,Gg8f6]
covering the d4-square. Our plan now is to gain space with f5, followed by
g6-Bg7 & 0-0 in most of the cases. We would then want to use the extra space
in the center to create chances of the kingside.} 3. g3 {White's main way of
playing.} ({another way of playing} 3. e3 {keeping the flexiblity between Be2/
Bg2. Nevertheless, we can opt for the typical structure with} f5 4. d4 Nf6 {
[%csl Ge5,Gf5][%cal Gf8b4,Yd7d6,Yg7g6,Yf8g7] where we intend to play Bb4 or
d6-Bg7, based on what White plays.}) ({the natural} 3. Nf3 {is met in the
typical fashion with} f5 4. d4 e4 {[%csl Ge4,Gf5] where we have a lot of space
in the center/kingside and keep healthy to attack White's kingside.}) 3... f5 {
a very interesting and dynamic way to play. we gain space on the flank.} 4. Bg2
Nf6 {This is an important tabiya, where White has several choices.} 5. d3 {
The main move by the number of games. White opens up the diagonal for the
bishop, and keeps flexibility between e3/e4.} ({another common way of playing
these positions} 5. e3 {intending Nge2-d4. We can stay true to our setup and
play} d6 6. Nge2 g6 7. d4 Bg7 8. O-O O-O {[%cal Ge5e4,Yg6g5,Gc6e7,Ge7g6] with
exciting play. Our usual plan in these positions is to play e4, gaining space
and shutting down the bishop, followed by g5-Ne7-Ng6.}) ({stopping Bb4 with} 5.
a3 {makes a lot of sense as well. Nevertheless, we can play the typical} g6 {
[%cal Gf8g7,Gd7d6,Ge8g8] followed by Bg7-d6-0-0 in some order.}) 5... d6 {
we defend d6 and wait for White to commit to a plan.} 6. e4 {the main sideline.
White wants to play Nge2-0-0-Nd5 next.} (6. Rb1 {[%cal Gb2b4,Gb4b5] an
interesting attempt. White delays Nf3 and wants to push b4-b5 very quickly. We
meet this with} a5 7. a3 {and now the novel} Nd4 $5 {[%csl Gd6,Ge5,Gf5][%cal
Gc7c6,Gd4e6] intending c6-Ne6.}) ({Another mainline arises with the typical} 6.
Nf3 {here I recommend going with our usual setup with} g6 7. O-O Bg7 {The key
theoretical discussion in these positions arises after} 8. Rb1 a5 9. a3 O-O 10.
b4 axb4 11. axb4 {where I recommend going for} Qe8 {[%cal Gc6d8,Yd8e6,Yg6g5] a
rather rare move, but a very strong one. We vacate the d8-square for the
knight, intending b5 Nd8-Ne6 and g5 at some point. Black keeps great dynamic
chances.}) 6... g6 {the key point arises after} 7. Nge2 Bg7 8. O-O f4 $5 {
Which has been tried in just one out of 1300 games. The position arising after}
9. gxf4 Nh5 $5 {[%csl Gc6,Gd8,Rf4,Gg7,Gh5,Gh8][%cal Gd8h4,Gg7e5,Ge8g8] Is
absolutely fine objectively, while giving Black tremendous attacking prospects
on the kingside.} *

