{[%evp 0,28,11,-13,-13,-28,11,-43,-38,-20,-20,-20,-18,-18,-25,-18,-16,-18,-7,
-10,3,-4,2,-3,8,11,23,-34,-17,-35,-15] Welcome to the first chapter of this
course. We'll start by examining 1.c4 e5 2.g3 and now the very rare and
inspiring h5!?} 1. c4 {With 1.c4, White gains space and prevents us indirectly
from playing d5. Doing so will result in a trade of our central pawn for
White's non-central pawn.} e5 {we gain space too, and prevent White from
playing d4 easily.} 2. g3 {as mentioned in the introduction, I find this very
slightly weaker than 2.Nc3 strategically, since White is not challenging the
center immediately. White's idea is to fianchetto their bishop next and exert
pressure over the h1-a8 diagonal, stopping us from playing d5 in the process.
Black's usual move here is to play c6, preparing to gain space with d5, but we
try to hit the 'hook' on the kingside with} h5 $5 ({another plausible
alternative is} 2... Nc6 3. Bg2 f5 {these lines are very similar to the 2.Nc3
lines and should transpose more often than not. If you don't want to repeat 2..
.h5 all the time or if you are a bit worried about the objectivity of 2...h5,
this can be a very good practical shortcut for you. I feel h5 can be a great
surprise weapon, and hence recommend it in the course.}) {White has several
alternatives for this move. We'll be going through all of them, except 3.Nf3.}
3. h4 {[%csl Rg4] stopping us physically from pushing h4. However, this
weakens the important g4-square.} (3. Bg2 h4 4. Nc3 {tr. transposes to the
next line.}) (3. Nc3 {White develops their knight} h4 {we continue to hammer
down the 'hook' with h4. We are threatening hxg3, so White needs to take a
decision about the g3 pawn.} 4. g4 $5 {the most ambitious way. White gains
space and prevents the exchange. Usually such advances are not great, but
since our pawn is on h4, we cannot attack the g4 pawn with another easily.
Playing f5 compromises king safety. Instead, we prioritise development.} (4.
Bg2 {isn't impressive. We can play} d6 {[%cal Gh4h3,Gb8c6] stopping g4, and
threatening to gain more space with h3. The bishop on g2 would then be
uncomfortable, probably heading to f3, where we develop our knight to c6 and
pose some uncomfortable questions in form of Nd4. developing the knight with}
5. Nf3 {doesn't help either, as after} h3 6. Bf1 g5 $1 {[%csl Rf1,Gg4,Gh3]
[%cal Gg5g4] gaining space and trying to lock down the bishop, Black is
slightly, better.}) 4... d5 $1 {[%csl Rg4] giving up the central pawn to
develop the bishop, and grab the kingside pawn.} 5. cxd5 {[%csl Rb8,Rd5][%cal
Gd5c6] this creates a set of doubled pawns, but stops us from playing Nc6.} (5.
Nxd5 Bxg4 {[%csl Rf1,Gh4][%cal Gb8c6] followed by Nc6 gives Black very easy
play. White has issue developing the f1-bishop due to h4-h3.}) 5... Bxg4 {
[%csl Gf1]} 6. h3 $1 {[%csl Rg4] the best way. White forces us to either allow
Nf3, or move the bishop back to h5.} (6. Bg2 {is not ideal. After} h3 7. Bf3 {
we have the strong response} Bc8 $5 $132 {[%csl Rg1][%cal Gf8c5,Gd8h4,Gb8d7,
Gg8h6] avoiding the bishop trade. White has issues with kingside development.}
({instead,} 7... Nf6 8. e4 $1 {would have allowed White to retain the center
and provoke a bishop trade.})) (6. d4 Nd7 $132 {[%cal Gf8d6,Yg8e7,Ye7g6,Gd8e7]
is also quite fine for Black. Just bring out your pieces to natural squares.})
6... Bh5 {we don't have the option of Bc8 anymore.} (6... Bf5 $6 7. Nf3 $16 {
[%csl Gf3] the knight can be developed easily here.}) 7. Bg2 Nd7 {we continue
to develop logically} 8. Nf3 Bd6 {[%cal Gg8e7,Gf7f5,Ye7g6] followed by Ne7-Ng6/
f5.} 9. d4 {the principled and critical try. White gains space and wants to
