preparing to strengthen the center with d5} 8. d3 (8. O-O h4 $15 {[%cal Gd8a5,
Ga5h5] gives Black good attacking chances.}) 8... exd3 9. Qxd3 h4 $1 {[%csl
Rg2][%cal Gh4h3] the usual motif.} 10. Nc3 h3 11. Bf3 Nbd7 $15 {[%csl Rc1,Rd3,
Rf3][%cal Gd7e5,Gd7c5] with Ne5/Nc5 coming up next, winning a tempo.}) (6.
Nxg7+ $4 Kf8 $19 {[%csl Rg7]}) 6... Qxe7 {[%cal Gh5h4,Gb8c6,Gc8f5,Gg8f6]} 7.
Nc3 {[%cal Gc3e4,Gc3d5] the most played move.White increases the pressure over
the e4-pawn and develops a piece.} (7. h4 {preventing h4 also makes sense.} Nc6
{we develop our pieces regardless} 8. Bg2 Bf5 9. Nc3 Nf6 10. O-O {[%cal Gd2d3]}
(10. b3 {is too slow. Black can start taking over with} O-O-O 11. Bb2 $2 Rhg8
$15 {[%cal Gg7g5,Ye1g1]}) 10... Qd7 $1 {[%csl Rg2][%cal Gf5h3] crucial. We
want to eliminate the advantage of bishop pair after White opens up the
position with d3.} (10... O-O-O $6 11. d3 $16 {[%csl Rb7,Gc1,Rg5][%cal Gb2b4,
Gb4b5,Gg2b7,Gc1g5]}) 11. d3 exd3 12. exd3 (12. e4 $5 {is an interesting
alternative. Regardless, after} Bh3 13. Qxd3 Bxg2 14. Kxg2 Ng4 $11 {[%cal
Gg4e5,Gc6d4,Yf7f6,Ye8c8,Yg7g5] we have a great position. We have ideas of
0-0-0-f6-g5, or Nge5-Nd4, or both.}) 12... O-O {[%csl Rd4,Rg2,Rg4][%cal Gf5h3]}
13. d4 (13. Re1 Rfe8 $11 {is quite fine too. We are happy to trade the rook
and bring the a8-rook into the game.}) (13. Bg5 $5 {is met with} Nh7 14. Bf4 (
14. Qxh5 $4 Bg4 $19) 14... Bg4 $1 15. Qd2 Nd4 $132) 13... Bg4 14. Qd3 Nb4 $1
15. Qd2 Rfe8 $11 {[%csl Rc1,Rf3,Rg2][%cal Gg4h3] followed by Bh3. White has
issues developing the c1-bishop}) 7... Nf6 {we defend e4/d5 and renew the
threat of h4.} 8. Bg2 (8. d3 exd3 9. Qxd3 Nbd7 {[%csl Rd3][%cal Gd7e5]} 10. Bg2
(10. h4 $6 Ne5 $1 {[%csl Rc4,Rd3][%cal Ge5f3]} 11. Qc2 Nf3+ 12. Kd1 Ne5 $15 {
[%csl Rd1]}) (10. Bg5 $2 Ne5 $17 11. Qe3 (11. Qd4 Nf3+ $19) 11... Nfg4 12. Bxe7
Nxe3 13. fxe3 Kxe7 $17 {[%csl Rc4,Re2,Re3,Ge5] Black remains better due to the
bad White bishop and White's poor pawn structure.}) 10... h4 $1 {transposes})
8... h4 {is precisely what we want.} 9. d3 (9. O-O Qe5 $1 $40 10. d3 Qh5 $1 {
[%csl Rg1][%cal Gh4g3,Gc8h3]}) 9... exd3 10. Qxd3 Nbd7 {[%cal Gd7e5,Gc8h3,
Yh4g3] the knight comes out with a tempo. You can stop memorising here. I have
included some lines for readers who wish to know a bit more about the plans in
the position.} 11. Bg5 (11. O-O Ne5 12. Qd4 hxg3 (12... Nc6 $5 {is a decent
alternative too}) 13. fxg3 (13. hxg3 Bh3 $17 {[%csl Rg2][%cal Gh8h1]}) 13... c5
$132 {[%csl Rc4,Ge5,Gf6][%cal Gc8e6,Ge8c8]}) 11... h3 $1 12. Bf3 Ne5 {[%csl
Rc4]} 13. Qe3 {[%cal Ge3e7,Gc3d5]} Be6 $1 {[%cal Ge5c4] not allowing the queen
trade} 14. Bxb7 Rb8 15. f4 (15. Be4 Rxb2 16. O-O Bxc4 $132 {[%csl Gb2,Re2,Re4]
[%cal Ge8g8,Ge7e3]}) 15... Rxb7 16. fxe5 Ng4 $1 {the crucial intermezzo. We
have sufficient compensation in the form of activity and king safety.} 17. Qf3
Qxg5 18. Qc6+ (18. Qxb7 O-O 19. exd6 cxd6 $44 {[%csl Re1,Ge6,Gg4,Gg5,Gh3][%cal
Gg4e3,Gg5e3]}) 18... Bd7 19. Qxb7 O-O 20. Qxc7 Be6 $44 {[%csl Re1,Gg4,Gg5,Gh3]
[%cal Gg5e3,Gg4e3] Black keeps good attacking chances. We intend to play Ne3/
Qe3 on the next move.} *

