{[%evp 0,42,19,-13,-13,-23,25,3,11,20,17,28,48,48,55,29,29,26,20,25,54,47,59,
40,48,12,12,16,24,34,23,30,22,37,37,19,44,44,52,24,61,24,40,29,27] In this
chapter, we'll cover all of White's options after 1.c4 e5 2.g3 h5!? 3. Nf3,
except for the 5.Nf5 line, which we examined in the previous chapter.} 1. c4 e5
2. g3 h5 $5 3. Nf3 e4 {we gain space and force White to make a decision with
the knight} 4. Nh4 $1 {the critical move. White isn't afraid of the knight
getting trapped.} ({other moves are significantly weaker} 4. Nd4 $6 {allows us
to bring our knight with a tempo} Nc6 $1 5. Nxc6 $6 (5. Nf5 $2 d5 $17 {[%csl
Rf5]}) (5. Nc2 {is quite passive. We can start making threats on the kingside
with} h4 6. Bg2 (6. Nc3 Nf6 7. Bg2 {transposes}) 6... Nf6 7. Nc3 h3 $1 {
[%csl Rg2] forcing White to give up the bishop} 8. Bxe4 Nxe4 9. Nxe4 d5 {
opening up the center since we have the pair of bishops.} 10. cxd5 Qxd5 $44 {
[%csl Gc8,Re1,Gf8,Gh3] Black has a great position thanks to the pair of
bishops and the pawn on h3.} 11. f3 Be6 12. d3 O-O-O $44 {[%csl Re1,Ge6,Gf8]
[%cal Gf8e7,Gf7f5,Gg7g5]}) 5... dxc6 $15 {[%csl Ge4,Gh5][%cal Gh5h4] even
though we have a set of doubled pawns, Black stands better strategically due
to the extra space (thanks to the pawn on e4) and the threat of h5-h4.} 6. Bg2
({trying to win the pawn with} 6. Nc3 {doesn't help either. We can attack the
hook with} h4 $1 $15 {[%cal Gh4g3,Yf2g3,Gf7f5] where Black is already slightly
better. It's important to note that} 7. Nxe4 {doesn't help either, as Black
keeps a very healthy advantage after} f5 8. Nc3 hxg3 9. fxg3 Bd6 $17 {[%csl
Gd6,Gd8,Rg3,Rh2][%cal Gh8h1]}) 6... h4 $1 {[%csl Rg3]} 7. Bxe4 Nf6 8. Bg2 Qd4
$1 {[%csl Rc4,Rf2,Rg3][%cal Gf8c5] the crucial point. We threaten Bc5/Qxc4.} 9.
d3 (9. Qb3 {runs into} Ng4 10. e3 (10. Qf3 Bc5 $17) 10... Qf6 $19 {[%csl Rf2,
Rg3,Rh2][%cal Gh4g3] where White is busted.}) 9... Ng4 {White is in grave
trouble. We have too many threats. Note that} 10. e3 {doesn't help, as after}
Bb4+ $19 {[%csl Rb2,Rd3,Re1][%cal Gd4b2,Gd4d3] both Bd2/Nd2 lose material one
way or the other.}) ({retreating with} 4. Ng1 $6 {doesn't make much sense
either. Black can continue with the typical with} h4 5. Bg2 {the natural Nf6
is fine, but even trickier is} c6 $1 {looking to meet} 6. Bxe4 {with} d5 $1 {
[%csl Re4]} 7. cxd5 cxd5 8. Bg2 (8. Bf3 Nc6 9. d4 Be6 {[%csl Rg1][%cal Gf8b4,
Gg8f6,Gd8d7] gives Black the typical compensation. White has problems
developing the g1-knight comfortably. trying to develop immediately with} 10.
e3 {runs into} Qd7 11. Ne2 g5 $17 {[%csl Rf3][%cal Gg5g4,Gh4h3,Gg8f6,Ge8c8]
threatening g4/h3. If that's not possible, we can always play Nf6/0-0-0.}) 8...
h3 {was our point.} 9. Bf3 g5 {[%csl Rf3,Rg1][%cal Gb8c6] White has issues
with the kingside development. something like} 10. e3 (10. Nc3 Nf6 {[%cal
Gg5g4]}) 10... Nc6 11. d4 Nf6 $44 {[%cal Gg5g4,Gc8f5] gives Black great
compensation.}) 4... Be7 {[%csl Rh4] hitting the knight} ({trying to trap the
knight with} 4... d6 $6 {doesn't work. White keeps a healthy advantage after}
5. Nc3 g5 6. Ng2 $16 {[%csl Re4,Rg5]}) 5. Nc3 $1 {this crucial move is the
critical line of this chapter. White is looking to give up a pawn to get a
lead in development and win the crucial dark-squared bishop. This is not easy
to play practically} ({other moves are weaker.} 5. Ng2 $6 {is quite passive.
We can try to strengthen our center with} c6 $1 {[%cal Gd7d5] if White tries
to undermine it with} 6. d3 {we can play} exd3 7. Qxd3 Nf6 {[%cal Gd7d5]} 8.
Nc3 Na6 $11 {[%csl Rd3,Rf1,Rg2][%cal Gd7d5,Ya6b4,Ya6c5,Yb4d5] with comfortable
play.}) (5. Bg2 {runs into} d5 6. cxd5 g5 $17 {[%csl Rh4] where the knight is
trapped.}) (5. Nf5 {is covered in the next chapter.}) 5... c6 $1 {[%cal Gd7d5]
looking to meet Nxe4 with d5, winning several tempos.} (5... Bxh4 $6 6. gxh4
Qxh4 7. d3 exd3 8. Qxd3 $16 {[%csl Rb8,Gc1,Rc8,Gf1,Rg7,Rg8][%cal Gh1g1] is
White's point. White has ideas of Rg1-Bg5/Nd5 in the air. Our pieces don't
come out in time.}) 6. d3 $1 (6. Bg2 $2 d5 7. cxd5 g5 $17 {[%csl Rh4]}) (6. Nf5
$5 d5 7. Nxe7 Nxe7 {[%csl Gd5,Ge4][%cal Gh5h4] we have a great center.} 8. d3 {
trying to undermine it.} exd3 9. Qxd3 d4 $1 {gaining space.} 10. Ne4 c5 {
[%csl Gc5,Gd4][%cal Gb8c6,Gb7b6,Gc8f5] the point. Black keeps great center
control.} 11. Bd2 (11. Bg2 Nbc6 12. O-O Bf5 $11) 11... Bf5 12. Bg2 Nbc6 $11 {
[%cal Gb7b6]}) (6. Nxe4 $6 {runs into} d5 7. cxd5 cxd5 8. Nc3 d4 9. Ne4 (9. Nb1
d3 $17 {[%csl Ra1,Rb1,Rc1,Rf1][%cal Gb8c6,Gc6d4]}) 9... g5 10. Nf3 f5 $1 {
[%csl Re4] the knight is trapped right in the center of the board!}) 6... exd3
7. Qxd3 d6 {[%cal Gb8d7,Gd7c5,Ge7f6,Yd7e5] looking to get the knight into the
action.} 8. Nf5 $1 {the strongest. White forces us to give up the bishop pair.}
(8. Bg2 Nd7 $132 {[%cal Gd7c5,Yd7e5] gives Black good play} 9. O-O {this
natural moves gives Black good play.} (9. Nf5 $2 Ne5 $15) (9. Qd4 Nc5 $1 {
exploiting that Qxg7 Bf6 is a queen trap.} 10. O-O Bf6 11. Qd2 Ne7 {[%csl Rc4,
Gc5,Gf6,Rh4][%cal Gc8e6,Gf6a1] gives Black a good fighting position
practically.}) 9... Ne5 10. Qe4 Bxh4 11. gxh4 Ne7 $132 {[%csl Rc4,Re4,Ge5,Ge7,
Gf7,Rh4][%cal Ge7f5] Black has a great position practically.}) 8... Bxf5 9.
Qxf5 Qd7 $1 {we invite to take on d7, so that our knight comes out for free.}
10. Qf4 $5 {the most testing move practically. White keeps the c4 pawn guarded
and avoids the queen trade.} (10. Qc2 {is a bit weaker. We can continue with
our natural play by playing} h4 {[%csl Rg3]} 11. Bg2 hxg3 12. hxg3 Rxh1+ 13.
Bxh1 Qh3 14. Bf3 Nd7 $132 {[%cal Gd7e5,Ge8c8] followed by Ne5 & 0-0-0. We keep
good practical chances.}) (10. Qd3 Qe6 {[%csl Rd3][%cal Gb8d7,Gd7c5] gives us
an extra tempo.} 11. h4 Nd7 12. b3 (12. Bh3 $2 Ne5 $1 13. Bxe6 Nxd3+ 14. exd3
fxe6 $11 {[%csl Rd3,Rd4][%cal Ge8d7,Gg8h6,Gh6f5]}) 12... Ngf6 $1 13. Bh3 (13.
Bg2 Nc5 14. Qc2 d5 15. cxd5 cxd5 $132 {[%csl Rc2,Rc3,Gc5,Gd5][%cal Ga8c8,Gc8c1]
}) 13... Ng4 $1 14. Bg2 (14. f3 $4 Nde5 15. Qe4 f5 $19 {[%csl Re1,Re2,Re4,Rf3]
[%cal Ge6e1]}) 14... Nc5 {[%csl Gc5,Ge7,Gg4][%cal Ge7f6,Ga7a5] followed by
a5-Bf6. We may even play g5, looking to attack the White king, if White
decides to castle short.}) (10. Qxd7+ Nxd7 $132 {helps us get our knight out
for no reason.} 11. h4 $5 {preventing h4} (11. Bg2 h4 $132 {[%cal Gg8f6,Ge8c8,
Gd7e5,Gd7c5] gives us the typical play.}) 11... Nc5 12. Bg2 a5 {[%csl Gc5]
[%cal Ga5b4] cementing the knight on c5.} 13. O-O Nf6 14. Rd1 O-O-O $132 {
[%csl Rc4][%cal Gf6d7,Gc8c7,Ge7f6]}) 10... h4 $1 {forcing} 11. g4 (11. Bg2 hxg3
12. hxg3 Rxh1+ 13. Bxh1 Qh3 {[%cal Gb8d7,Gg8f6,Gd7e5,Ge8c8] gives us the
typical chances we want.}) 11... Qe6 {[%csl Rc4,Ge6][%cal Ge6c4] preparing
Nd7-Ne5.} 12. Qe4 $1 {the crucial point. White invites us to capture on e4 to
centralise the knight. I think it's practically impossible for White to play
with such precision in a practical game.} (12. g5 Nd7 $132 {[%csl Rc4,Rg5]
[%cal Gd7e5,Gd7c5] gives us the typical play we aim for.}) 12... Qxe4 {forced,
as White intended to spoil our structure further with Qxe6} (12... Nd7 $6 13.
Qxe6 fxe6 14. g5 $16 {[%cal Gf1h3]}) 13. Nxe4 {[%csl Rd6]} Nd7 {[%cal Gd7e5,
Gg8f6] We stand fine if we are able to play Nf6/Ne5 in time, but White can
stop that with} 14. Bf4 $1 {[%csl Rd6]} (14. b3 Ngf6 {gives us a very
comfortable game. A sample line-} 15. Nxf6+ Bxf6 16. Rb1 Nc5 $11 {[%cal Ga7a5,
Ga5a4,Yc5e4,Re8c8,Rh8e8,Ye4c3] with several ideas.}) 14... d5 $1 {forced} (
14... Ne5 $6 15. c5 $16) 15. cxd5 cxd5 16. Nd6+ (16. Nc3 {is a decent
alternative too. We can't afford to give up the d5 pawn, so we play} Bb4 17.
O-O-O Bxc3 18. bxc3 Rc8 19. Rxd5 Ngf6 20. Rd4 Nc5 {[%csl Ra2,Rc3,Gc8][%cal
Gc5e4,Gf6e4,Ge8g8] where White keeps a small edge due to the pair of bishops,
but we are still very much in the game thanks to the activity of our pieces.})
16... Bxd6 17. Bxd6 Rh6 $1 {[%cal Gh6a6] a crucial move. We bring all of our
pieces into the game.} 18. Ba3 {the most crucial attempt. White keeps an eye
on the e7 square.} (18. Bf4 {isn't dangerous. After} Rg6 19. h3 Rc8 $11 {
[%cal Gg8e7,Gc8c2] we stand fine, thanks to the activity of our pieces.}) 18...
Rc8 {getting the rook into the game.} 19. g5 (19. Bg2 $1 Ne7 $132 {[%csl Rc2,
Re2,Rg4][%cal Gc8c4,Gh6e6] isn't a problem for us. We have ideas of Re6-Rc4/
Rc2, giving ample compensation.}) 19... Re6 $1 {[%csl Re2][%cal Gc8c2] the
best practical try in my opinion.} (19... Rg6 $5 20. Rg1 Ne7 {[%cal Gd7e5] is
a decent alternative.}) 20. Bh3 (20. Bg2 Ne7 21. Bxe7 Kxe7 22. Bxd5 Re5 $11 {
[%csl Rb2,Re2][%cal Gc8c2] gives us a very comfortable position.}) (20. Kd2 {
[%cal Gd2c2] the strongest move objectively. White covers the c2-square.} Rec6
21. Bh3 Rc2+ 22. Kd1 Ne7 $14 {[%cal Gc2c4,Gc4d4] White is objectively slightly
better here, but we keep practical chances due to the activity of our pieces.})
20... Re5 21. Rg1 Rc2 $132 {[%csl Gc2,Re2,Ge5][%cal Gg8e7,Ge5g5,Gc2b2] gives
sufficient compensation.} *

