{[%evp 0,40,11,-13,-13,-11,-11,-23,12,5,8,8,25,22,21,19,19,32,20,24,21,16,16,
27,38,60,87,74,67,33,34,29,71,71,71,65,65,57,63,70,76,76,78] Welcome to the
next section of chapters, where we cover 2.Nc3 for White. The positions are
completely different from the previous chapters. The 2...h5 lines were largely
concrete, while these are more thematic in nature.} 1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nc6 {
the starting point of the system. White has several ways to play here, but we
will start with the main one, the fianchetto system.} 3. g3 f5 {[%csl Ge5,Gf5]
[%cal Gg7g6,Gf8g7,Gg8f6,Gd7d6,Yg6g5,Yc6e7,Ye7g6,Ge5e4,Yf5f4,Rh7h5,Rh5h4] the
point. We gain a lot of space in the center. Our usual plan is these positions
is to play Nf6-g6-Bg7 followed by either g5-Ne7-Ng6 or further gaining space
with e4. In some variations, we might even throw in h5-h4.} 4. Bg2 Nf6 5. e3 {
[%cal Gd2d4] one of two main lines. White intends to gain space in the center
with d4.} (5. d3 {is the most popular move, which is covered in the subsequent
chapters.}) 5... d6 {we continue our plan of developing normally} 6. Nge2 g6 7.
O-O (7. d4 $5 {this usually transposes to the main line with 0-0, but there
are a few independent tries for White.} Bg7 8. b4 {[%cal Gb4b5,Gg2b7] the main
independent try for White. White wants to play b5 and open up the
h1-a8-diagonal.} (8. Bxc6+ {is possible, but not too threatening.} bxc6 9. dxe5
dxe5 10. Qxd8+ Kxd8 {even though we have the doubled pawns, it's very
difficult for White to attack them. On the other hand, Black has the pair of
bishops and space in the center. I find this position slightly easier to play
for Black. There's just one plan which you need to know.} 11. b3 {[%cal Gc1a3,
Ge1c1]} Ke7 $1 12. Ba3+ Kf7 $11 {[%cal Gg6g5,Gf5f4,Gh7h5,Ge5e4] followed by
plans of g5-h5-f4/e4/h4, increasing space.}) (8. O-O {transposes to the main
line of the chapter.}) 8... a6 {a rare but a strong move. We play a6 in a lot
of these variations. The idea is to meet b5 with axb5, opening up the file for
the rook.} 9. O-O O-O 10. Qb3 {comp's top choice.} (10. Rb1 {is quite similar
to 10.Qb3. After} e4 11. f3 exf3 12. Bxf3 g5 $132 {[%csl Re3][%cal Gc6e7,Ge7g6,
Yd8e8,Ye8g6,Gc8d7,Ga8e8] we have a dynamic position on the board.}) 10... e4 {
gaining space, shutting the bishop down.} 11. f3 {this eliminates our space
advantage, but after} exf3 12. Bxf3 Kh8 {[%cal Gg6g5,Gc8d7,Gd8e8,Yc6e7,Ye7g6,
Ge8g6] getting rid of the pin, we keep dynamic chances.}) 7... Bg7 8. d4 {
the main move. White gains space in the center. The other non-d4 setups are
covered in the subsequent chapters.} O-O {We'll cover all the lines for White
except for 9.Rb1.} 9. b3 {[%cal Gc1b2] the main move. White is looking to
improve pieces in a slow fashion.} (9. dxe5 {is not impressive.} dxe5 {[%csl
Ge5,Gf5][%cal Ge5e4] we get a huge center and prepare e5-e4} 10. e4 $5 {
the most testing line} (10. Qxd8 Rxd8 11. e4 Nb4 $15 {[%csl Rd3,Rd4] is quite
good for Black}) 10... Qxd1 11. Rxd1 fxe4 12. Nxe4 (12. Bg5 Bg4 $11) 12... Bg4
$5 13. N4c3 e4 14. h3 Bf3 $11) (9. d5 {[%csl Rc5] gives us the important c5
square. Usually, d4-d5 in such structures is not ideal.} Nb8 {[%csl Rc5]} 10.
e4 a5 {[%cal Gb8a6,Ga6c5]} 11. exf5 (11. f4 Nxe4 $11) 11... gxf5 {[%cal Gd8e8,
Ge8g6,Gb8a6,Gc8d7] with a sharp middlegame.}) (9. a3 e4 10. b4 Ne7 {[%cal
Gd6d5,Gg6g5] with typical plans of g5 and d5 coming up next.}) (9. Nd5 e4 {
following our plan of gaining space} 10. Nxf6+ Qxf6 {[%cal Gc6d8,Gd8e6,Yc6b8,
Yb8d7,Yd7f6,Ge6g5] we now look to improve our c6-knight. Our plans are
Nb8-d7-f6, or Nd8-e6-g5.} 11. Bd2 {[%cal Gb2b4]} (11. Nf4 Nd8 {[%cal Gc7c6]}
12. f3 exf3 13. Bxf3 Ne6 14. Nd5 Qd8 $11 {[%csl Re3] we are preparing c6-Ng5
next. We'll look to put pressure on e4/e3.}) (11. b3 Nd8 12. Bb2 Qe7 {getting
out of the pin} 13. Qd2 Ne6 {[%cal Ge6g5,Gh7h5]} 14. h4 Bd7 $132 {[%cal Ga8e8,
Gg6g5]}) 11... Qe7 12. b4 (12. Nf4 Nd8 13. b4 c6 $11 {[%cal Gd8e6]}) 12... Nb8
{this time, we head for f6.} (12... Nd8 13. Rc1 Ne6 14. h4 {[%cal Gd4d5] is
White's point. We have some issues with our knight}) 13. Nf4 Nd7 14. b5 Nf6 15.
a4 g5 $132) 9... e4 {[%csl Rd3] locking the d3-outpost.} 10. f3 (10. Bb2 {
runs into} Nb4 $1 {[%cal Gb4d3,Yc7c6,Gc7c5]} 11. f3 {the only challenging move.
} Nd3 $5 12. Ba3 Re8 13. fxe4 fxe4 14. Nxe4 Nxe4 15. Qxd3 Bf5 $44 {[%csl Ge4,
Gf5,Rg3][%cal Gd8g5,Gh7h5,Gh5h4]}) (10. Nf4 Ne7 $15 {[%cal Gg6g5]}) 10... exf3
11. Bxf3 Ne7 {[%csl Re3][%cal Gc7c6,Gg6g5,Ge7g6] followed by c6/g5-Ng6. We
then want to put pressure on the e3-pawn.} 12. Bb2 (12. Qd2 c6 13. Ba3 g5 {
[%csl Re3][%cal Ge7g6,Gf8e8,Ga8b8,Gb7b5,Gd6d5]} 14. e4 h6 $11) (12. Nf4 c6 13.
Bb2 g5 $1 14. Nd3 Ng6 $11 {[%csl Re3][%cal Gc8e6,Gd6d5,Gf8e8]}) 12... d5 13.
Nf4 c6 14. Qc2 g5 15. Nd3 Re8 {[%cal Ge7g6] playing ambitiously.} ({the best
move objectively is} 15... Be6 {[%cal Gd5c4] but White has a repetition with}
16. Nc5 (16. c5 Ng6 $17 {[%csl Re3,Rg3][%cal Gh7h5,Gh5h4,Yf6g4]}) 16... Bc8 17.
Nd3 $11) 16. Rae1 (16. Ne5 Be6 17. Rae1 Ng6 {is quite good for us. Nxg6 hxg6
strengthens our f5-pawn}) 16... Rb8 $5 {[%cal Gb8b7,Gb7b5]} (16... Be6 $11) 17.
Ne5 b5 $132 18. cxd5 cxd5 19. a4 b4 20. Nb5 g4 $132 {[%csl Rb5][%cal Gc8a6,
Gd8b6]} *

