{[%evp 0,36,11,-13,-11,-11,-11,-31,5,8,8,0,25,22,21,24,24,24,24,13,26,26,32,31,
42,27,31,24,30,30,48,19,23,-5,55,-8,15,-5,14]} 1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3 f5 4.
Bg2 Nf6 5. e3 d6 6. Nge2 g6 7. O-O Bg7 8. d4 O-O 9. Rb1 {[%cal Gb2b4,Gb4b5]
the starting point of the current chapter. White goes for the more direct plan
of b4-b5 without wasting any time.} e4 {we follow our plan of gaining space in
the center} (9... a5 {is another possible alternative, which we cover in the
next chapter through a different move order.}) 10. f3 {the critical system.
White immediately challenges our center.} (10. b4 {we stay consistent with our
plan in the main line and play the thematic} Qe8 $1 11. b5 {principled, but
weaker} (11. f3 exf3 12. Bxf3 {transposes to the main line}) 11... Na5 {
[%csl Rc4] White has some problems with the pawn on c4.} 12. Qa4 (12. c5 $6 Be6
$15 {[%cal Ge6c4,Gb7b6]}) 12... b6 $11 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Ge8f7]}) 10... exf3 11.
Bxf3 Qe8 $1 $146 {[%csl Re3][%cal Gf6e4,Yc6d8,Yd8e6,Ye6g5] a multi-purpose
move. The queen aims the weaknesses on e4/e3, as well as creates space for the
knight to move to d8.} 12. b4 (12. Nf4 Nd8 {our thematic plan} 13. Ncd5 Nxd5
14. Bxd5+ (14. cxd5 Nf7 $15 {[%csl Rd5,Re4][%cal Gf7g5]}) 14... Nf7 15. b4 c6
16. Bg2 Bd7 $132 {[%cal Gf7g5,Ge8e7,Yf7h6,Yh6g4] followed by Ng5/Nh6-g4. The
position is dynamically balanced}) 12... Nd8 13. Nf4 c6 14. b5 Nf7 15. Bg2 {
prophylaxis against Ng5} (15. bxc6 bxc6 {[%cal Gc8d7,Ge8e7] doesn't change
much. We keep the thematic plans.}) 15... Ng5 16. a4 Bd7 17. a5 {[%cal Gb5c6,
Gb1b7] White is now threatening bxc6-Rb7/a6, so we prepare against this with}
Rf7 $1 $132 {[%cal Yf7e7,Gg5e4] with ideas of Ne4/Re7 in the air. If required,
we'll defend c6 with Rc8. Note that} 18. a6 {is met comfortably with} b6 {
[%cal Gg5e4] followed by Nge4, shutting down the diagonal.} *

