{[%evp 0,28,11,-13,-11,-11,-11,-31,8,8,0,8,25,24,24,24,24,0,2,-3,19,11,19,14,
-4,2,30,29,32,38,44]} 1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3 f5 4. Bg2 Nf6 5. e3 d6 {
the starting point of this chapter. We'll cover White's attempts with
e3+non-d4 tries.} 6. Nge2 (6. d3 {doesn't have a great independent value. After
} g6 7. Nge2 Bg7 8. O-O O-O {we transpose to the 8.d3 variation.}) 6... g6 7.
O-O Bg7 8. d3 {[%cal Ge5e4,Rd3e4,Ga1b1,Gb2b4] the main alternative of 8.d4.
White doesn't rush with 8.d4 and stops us from pushing e4.} (8. Rb1 a5 $5 {
It's important to play a5 and prevent b4 in this case. White hasn't committed
to d4, so we don't have the plan of e5-e4 anymore.} (8... O-O 9. b4 e4 10. d3
$1 $14 {is the point behind this subtle move order.}) 9. a3 {[%cal Gb2b4]
intending b4.} ({White can try to outsmart us in move orders with} 9. d4 {
but this is not too troubling. We can safely play} O-O {[%cal Ge5e4] with the
typical plan of e5-e4 coming up next.} 10. b3 (10. dxe5 dxe5 $11 {[%csl Rd3]
[%cal Gc6b4,Ge5e4,Gb4d3] is quite fine for us. We intend to play Nb4-e4-Nd3
next.}) 10... e4 {[%cal Yd8e8,Gc6b4,Gg6g5,Yc6d8] with ideas of Qe8-g5/Nd8 or
Nb4-Nd3 next.}) 9... O-O 10. b4 axb4 11. axb4 {[%cal Ga8a1] we have a better
version when compared to 8...0-0, since our rook is on an active file.} e4 {
the right time to push. We aren't afraid of} 12. d3 {as after} exd3 13. Qxd3
Ne5 14. Qc2 c6 {[%cal Gc8e6,Ye5c4,Yd8e7] we have a much better version of 8...
0-0. The rook on a8 is quite active. We intend Be6/Nc4/Qe7 next.}) (8. b3 $5 {
White wants to play a slow game with Bb2-d3 next.} O-O {the most natural and
consistent continuation.} ({that being said,} 8... h5 $5 $146 {is a very
interesting attempt too. You are free to explore this on your own.} 9. h4 (9.
Bb2 h4 $15 {[%cal Ge5e4,Gc6e5,Gh4g3] gives Black the initiative he hopes for.})
9... Ng4 {an ambitious attempt, aimed to meet} 10. d4 {with} g5 $5 {some
sample lines-} 11. f3 (11. hxg5 h4 $5 $132) 11... gxh4 $5 12. fxg4 hxg4 $5 {
with great practical chances.}) 9. Bb2 (9. d4 {transposes to the d4 lines})
9... Ne7 {[%cal Gc7c6] going for the typical c6-g5-Ng6/Be6 plan.} 10. d3 (10.
d4 {has been played in some games, but isn't too threatening. We can play the
thematic} e4 {and after} 11. f3 exf3 12. Bxf3 d5 {[%csl Re3][%cal Gc7c6,Gg6g5,
Ge7g6,Gf8e8] we have a typical structure arising. We want to play c6 next,
followed by g5-Ng6, followed by putting pressure on e3 with Re8/Qe7/Bd7/Rae8.})
(10. Rc1 {a very interesting attempt, aimed against our setup of c6-e4.} c6 {
we shut down the g2-bishop nevertheless} 11. d4 g5 $1 {[%cal Ge7g6,Ge5e4] a
very important subtletly. We now intend to play e4/Ng6.} (11... e4 {[%cal
Gd6d5,Gg6g5]} 12. d5 $5 {[%csl Rc6,Rd6][%cal Gb2a3,Gd5c6] was White's point.})
12. f3 (12. Qc2 $6 e4 $15) (12. dxe5 dxe5 $11) 12... Ng6 {[%csl Re3,Rg3][%cal
Gf5f4,Yg5g4,Gd8e7] gives us great practical chances, thanks to weak pawns.})
10... c6 {[%cal Gg6g5]} 11. Qd2 {White is avoiding d4 and preparing f4. We
cannot play g5 anymore due to f4!} Be6 {[%cal Gf8e8,Gd8c7,Ga8d8] going for the
Qc7-Rfe8-Rad8 formation.} 12. f4 $5 {finally!} Qc7 {we defend our weak pawn on
e5 and connect our rooks.} 13. Rae1 Rae8 $5 {[%cal Ga7a6,Gb7b5,Gf6d7,Gd7c5]
the most combative. We keep tension on the board, prevent e4 (by keeping a
rook on f8) and prepare a6-b5. The position is extremely tense, giving us
great practical chances.}) 8... O-O {We finish our kingside development. White
now has a couple of decent tries.} 9. Rb1 {[%cal Gb2b4,Gb4b5] played by
players like Vidit, Tari, Gukesh etc. Clearly the main move of the chapter.
White intends b4-b5.} (9. Nd5 {[%cal Ge2c3] intending to bring in the bad
e2-knight into the game.} Nxd5 {we don't give White the time to lodge a knight
on d5.} 10. cxd5 {[%csl Rc7][%cal Gc1d2,Ga1c1] the critical response. White
wants to play Bd2-Rc1 next, putting pressure on the c7-pawn.} Ne7 11. Bd2 c6 $1
{not giving White the opportunity to lock down the c7-pawn with Rc1.} 12. dxc6
bxc6 $11 {[%csl Gc6,Gd6,Ge5,Gf5][%cal Gc8e6,Gd8d7]}) (9. b3 Ne7 10. Bb2 {
transposes}) 9... a5 {A good rule of thumb is to meet d3-Rb1 with a5, and
d4-Rb1 with e4.} 10. a3 Ne7 {typical} 11. b4 ({White also had the extra option
of playing} 11. f4 {increasing tension. We can meet this in the thematic way
by playing} c6 {[%csl Rg2]} 12. b4 axb4 13. axb4 Be6 $11 {[%csl Rd3][%cal
Ye5e4,Gd8c7] with Qc7 coming up next. We also keep ideas of pushing e4 alive.})
11... axb4 12. axb4 g5 $1 {aimed against White's f4.} (12... c6 $11 {was a
very decent way of playing too.}) {if White tries} 13. f4 {regardless, we can
play} gxf4 14. exf4 c6 $11 {[%csl Rc4,Rd3][%cal Gf6g4,Gc8e6,Ye5e4,Gd8d7] with
ideas of Be6-e4, or Be6-Ng4-Qd7 next.} *

