{[%evp 0,34,11,-13,-11,-11,-11,-31,8,8,8,1,15,15,25,25,25,15,25,22,18,18,18,-7,
-7,-2,-2,17,-4,18,37,17,17,16,37,32,32]} 1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3 f5 4. Bg2
Nf6 5. d3 {the starting point of this chapter. White doesn't commit to e3.
This takes away Black's option of e4, but White has two disadvantages. Firstly,
the knight has to move to f3, losing some flexibility. Secondly, the option of
e3-d4 is taken away.} d6 {as usual, we start by playing 5...d6, keeping some
flexibliity. White now has three critical moves- Rb1, Nf3,a3 & and e4. We'll
cover all the options apart from 6. e4 in this chapter.} 6. Nf3 {the main move.
White develops their knight.} (6. Rb1 a5 {we stay consistent with the strategy
of meeting non e3-d4 lines with a5.} 7. a3 {White is intending to play b4 next.
} ({is met comfortably with the typical} 7. e3 g6 8. Nge2 Bg7 {transposing to
the previous chapters}) 7... Nd4 $1 {[%cal Gc7c6,Gd4e6,Gg7g6] a very smart
move order, intended against b4-b5.} 8. e3 (8. b4 axb4 9. axb4 Be7 {was our
point. We don't spend time on g6-Bg7 anymore. After the typical} 10. e3 Ne6 11.
Nge2 O-O {[%cal Gc7c6,Gd8e8,Ge8h5,Ge6g5] we have the extra option of
c6-Qe8-Qh5-Ng5.}) 8... Ne6 9. f4 $5 {a very ambitious way of restricting our
mobility. However, this weakens e3.} (9. Nge2 {is met with the typical} g6 10.
b4 axb4 11. axb4 Bg7 $132 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gc7c6,Yg6g5,Yg5g4,Yh7h5,Ye6g5] with
ideas of h5/0-0-g5-g4-Ng4 in the air. We'll also include c6 at some point.})
9... g6 10. Nf3 exf4 $1 11. exf4 Bg7 $132 {[%csl Rd4,Ge6][%cal Gc7c6,Ge8g8,
Gh8e8,Gc8d7] folllowed by 0-0-c6-Re8-Bd7. We always have those Ng4-Qb6 tricks.
Black is completely due to dark-squared weaknesses in White's camp.}) (6. a3 g6
{is quite to similar to 5.a3 g6, which we cover in one of the subsequent
chapters. The only independent attempt is} 7. b4 {attempting to gain space
directly. We are not bothered and play} Bg7 {[%csl Ra1,Rc3][%cal Gg7a1]} 8. Bb2
{this reduces pressure on the a1-h8 diagonal but allows Black to gain space on
the kingside with} (8. e3 {allows Black to gain space and weaken the
light-squares with} e4 {[%csl Rd3][%cal Gg7a1] exploiting the pin on the a1-h8
diagonal.}) 8... f4 $1 {stopping e3, thus forcing} 9. Nf3 {after} O-O 10. O-O {
we have the important} Nd4 $1 {looking to trade the inactive knight. White's
most testing move seems} 11. Nxd4 {but after} (11. c5 Be6 $11 {[%csl Gd4][%cal
Ge6b3,Gd4b3,Gd8d7,Ge6h3] is a dream position for Black.}) 11... exd4 12. Nd5
Nxd5 13. Bxd5+ Kh8 $11 {[%csl Rg1][%cal Gc7c6,Gc8g4] Black has nothing to
worry about. The d4 pawn is more of a strength than weakness, as it cannot be
attacked easily.}) 6... g6 {we stay consistent with our plan of playing g6-Bg7}
7. O-O Bg7 {White has a few options here.} 8. Rb1 {[%cal Gb2b4,Gb4b5] the main
move, preparing b4-b5} (8. Bg5 {looking to play Bxf6-Nd5. However, we don't
mind the trade, as we win the pair of bishops.} h6 9. Bxf6 Qxf6 10. Nd5 (10.
Rb1 {is met by the thematic} a5 11. a3 O-O 12. Nd5 (12. b4 Ne7 $132 {[%cal
Gg6g5]}) 12... Qf7 {[%cal Gc6d8,Gd8e6,Gg6g5] followed by Nd8-Ne6}) 10... Qf7
11. b4 O-O 12. b5 Nd8 $132 {[%cal Gc7c6,Gd8e6] followed by Ne6-c6-Bd7.}) (8.
Qc2 {is the comp's choice, but doesn't look terribly impressive. We can
continue with the natural} O-O {and after} 9. Rb1 {start gaining space on the
kingside with} h6 10. b4 g5 {[%cal Gc6e7,Gc8e6,Gc7c6] with a sharp and dynamic
position on the board.}) 8... a5 {as usual, we meet Rb1 with a5. The next few
moves are obvious.} 9. a3 O-O 10. b4 axb4 11. axb4 Qe8 $5 {[%cal Gc6d8,Gc7c6,
Yd8f7,Yd8e6] the key move in this variation. This move is quite useful, as we
not only threaten e4 in some cases, but also vacate the d8 square for the
knight, and thus prepare Nd8-e6.} 12. b5 Nd8 {[%cal Gd8e6,Gg6g5,Ye6c5]} 13. Bb2
{the most played move. White develops the last minor piece} (13. Nd5 {was
played in one of the game, but this weakens b5 after} Nxd5 14. cxd5 Bd7 $132 {
[%csl Rb5][%cal Gb7b6,Gd8b7,Gb7c5]}) 13... Ne6 {we bring our knight to the
most active square} 14. Nd2 {a very logical way to stop b6.} (14. Ra1 {played
by two strong GM's, Mareco & Pantsulaia. We look to finish our queenside
development with} Rxa1 15. Qxa1 b6 {[%cal Gc8b7,Yf5f4] intending Bb7, with
absolutely no problems. the other idea here is to push e4/f4.} 16. Nd2 (16. Qa7
{allows us to create counterplay with} e4 $132) 16... g5 $5 {[%cal Ge8h5,Gh7h5,
Gh5h4] gives us good chances on the kingside. A sample line-} 17. Nd5 Nxd5 18.
Bxd5 h5 {[%cal Gh5h4,Gf5f4,Ge5e4] with some pawn break coming up next.}) {
However, Nd2 allows us to create chances on the kingside with} 14... h5 $1 $132
{[%cal Gg6g5,Gh5h4]} 15. e3 g5 {[%csl Ge5,Gf5,Gg5,Gh5]} 16. Nd5 g4 17. Qc2 h4
$132 {with great attacking prospects on the kingside.} *

