{[%evp 0,30,11,-13,-11,-11,-11,-31,8,8,10,0,15,-29,0,6,6,-5,54,62,66,42,92,46,
46,39,-5,0,0,-34,-34,-36,0]} 1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3 f5 4. Bg2 Nf6 5. d3 d6 {
the point of deviation from the previous chapter. White gains space in the
center and heads for the setup with Nge2,0-0,h3,Be3, f4. It's particularly
annoying when we have played f5&e5 with the knight on f6 (and not on e7) as it
becomes harder for us to maintain tension in the center. Nevertheless, we have
a strong response planned.} 6. e4 $5 {[%csl Re5,Rf5][%cal Gg1e2,Ge1g1,Gh2h3,
Gc1e3,Gf2f4]} g6 {[%cal Gf8g7,Ge8g8] following the thematic plan with Bg7 &
0-0, but with a twist.} 7. Nge2 Bg7 8. O-O {[%cal Gf2f4,Yc3d5] White is ready
to meet 0-0 with f4, and so we start by playing} f4 $1 {a very strong move,
stopping White from pushing f4, and inducing weaknesses on White's kingside.
This has been played in just out of 1200 games.} 9. gxf4 O-O {[%csl Rd4,Re3,
Rf4,Rh2,Rh4][%cal Gf6h5] threatening Nh5. We want to build a grip over the
dark-squares on the kingside.} 10. Nd5 $5 {one of the most logical moves,
transposing to a line with a bunch of games.} (10. Be3 {is one of the comp's
top choice, but looks quite unnatural.} Nh5 {we continue with our thematic plan
} 11. f5 {with the idea of pushing f4 next.} (11. fxe5 dxe5 {[%csl Rd4,Rf4]
[%cal Gc6d4,Gh5f4] is our dream. We want to lodge our knight onto those juicy
outposts next!} 12. Qd2 {preparing f4} (12. f3 Nd4 $44 {[%csl Gd4,Re3,Rf4,Rh4]}
) 12... Nd4 $1 13. f4 $5 exf4 14. Nxf4 Nxf4 15. Rxf4 Rxf4 16. Bxf4 Bg4 $1 {
[%cal Gd4f3] developing the last minor piece with a threat} 17. Rf1 Qd7 {
[%cal Ga8f8]} 18. e5 c6 $44 {[%csl Rd4,Re3,Re5,Gg7][%cal Ga8f8,Gd4e6] with
great compensation.}) 11... Nd4 $1 ({was quite possible too.} 11... gxf5 $11)
12. f4 (12. Kh1 {with the idea of Rg1 is possible, but after} Kh8 13. Rg1 c6 {
[%cal Gg6f5] intending gxf5, Black has no problems whatsoever. fxg6 hxg6 opens
up files/diagonals for our pieces.}) 12... Nxe2+ 13. Qxe2 (13. Nxe2 gxf5 $11 {
gives Black a comfortable game}) 13... exf4 $1 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gg7c3]} 14.
Bxf4 Nxf4 15. Rxf4 Be5 {with a dream KID for Black. The bishop on e5 is a
monster.} 16. Rf3 gxf5 17. Raf1 f4 $15 {[%csl Ge5,Gf4][%cal Gd8g5,Gc8g4]}) (10.
fxe5 dxe5 11. f4 $6 {weakens the dark-squares significantly. Black keeps an
edge after} exf4 12. Bxf4 Nh5 13. Be3 Rxf1+ 14. Qxf1 Ne5 $11 {[%csl Rd3,Rd4,
Ge5,Rf4,Gh5][%cal Ge5g4,Gd8d3,Ge5c4]}) ({a very creative way of playing is} 10.
Kh1 {with the idea to play Rg1 next. However, Black is quite fine after the
natural} Nh5 11. f5 Qh4 12. Rg1 {threatening Bf1/ Bf3-Bg5.} Nf6 $1 {[%cal
Gf6g4]} (12... Qxf2 $4 13. Bg5 $18 {[%cal Gd1d2,Ga1f1]}) 13. Bf3 Qxf2 $11)
10... Nh5 {we continue with our plan of putting pressure on the dark-squares}
11. f5 $5 {trying to undermine the knight on h5.} (11. fxe5 dxe5 12. Be3 Nd4
$44 {[%cal Gh5f4,Yd4e2,Gc7c6] threatening c6, followed by Bg4 or Nf4.}) 11...
gxf5 12. Ng3 $5 {the point. Nxg3 fxg3! gives White the nagging positional
pressure he dreams of. Rather than that, we continue with our plan of
dominating the light-squares with} (12. exf5 Bxf5 $11 {gives Black a very
comfortable game.}) 12... Nf4 $1 {with the following concrete sequence in mind-
} 13. Nxf4 exf4 14. Bxf4 fxe4 15. Be3 Qh4 $44 {[%cal Gc8h3,Gc6e5] Black has
great attacking chances on the kingside with Bh3/Ne5 coming up next.} *

