{[%evp 0,26,11,-11,-11,-11,-11,-32,8,10,10,-4,5,15,15,25,20,20,28,-13,8,3,35,
21,21,15,25,38,62] Welcome to the final chapter on the fianchetto system. In
this chapter, we will go through White's move 5 alternatives.} 1. c4 e5 2. Nc3
Nc6 3. g3 f5 4. Bg2 Nf6 {the starting point. We'll cover 5.a3, 5.Nf3 & 5.b3
for White.} 5. a3 {[%cal Gb2b4] intending to gain space with b4. An ambitious
way of playing, but White neglects the development on the kingside.} (5. Nf3 {
this provokes us to play} e4 {which we accept!} 6. Ng1 $5 {White's point. he
is looking to play d3 next, trying to undermine our center. We meet this plan
by strengthening our center with} (6. Nh4 $6 {is significantly weaker. After}
d5 {[%csl Rh4][%cal Gf8e7,Ge7h4] the knight is always subject to an attack.})
6... d5 {[%csl Gd5,Ge4,Gf5]} 7. cxd5 Nxd5 8. d3 {the critical test.} Be6 {
[%cal Ga8d8] the critical move to remember. The point is revealed after} 9.
dxe4 (9. Nh3 {[%csl Re6][%cal Gh3g5] is the best move objectively. White
threatens Ng5.} h6 $1 {[%cal Gh6g5]} 10. dxe4 {the critical try.} (10. Nf4 Nxf4
11. Bxf4 g5 12. Be3 exd3 $11 {gives us a very comfortable position.} 13. exd3
Qd7 {[%csl Rd3,Rd4,Re1][%cal Ge8c8,Gf5f4,Gf8g7,Gc6d4]}) 10... Nxc3 $1 11. Qxd8+
Rxd8 12. bxc3 fxe4 {[%csl Rh3] exploiting the loose knight. After} 13. Nf4 Bf5
$11 {the position is balanced.}) 9... Nxc3 10. bxc3 {the only move which
survives.} (10. Qxd8+ $4 {looks tempting, but White faces a cold shower after}
Rxd8 11. bxc3 Nb4 $19 {[%cal Gb4c2,Gf8b4,Gd8d1] with huge material losses/mate
coming up next.}) 10... Qxd1+ 11. Kxd1 O-O-O+ 12. Kc2 Bc5 $44 {[%csl Ra1,Rc1,
Rc2,Gc5,Gc6,Re2,Ge6,Rf2,Rg1,Rh1] we have all the pieces jumping into the game.
Black has more than sufficient compensation.}) (5. b3 {is a possible way, but
should transpose to the e3 lines after a few moves. For example, after} g6 6.
Bb2 Bg7 {White has nothing better than} 7. e3 O-O 8. Nge2 d6 {where both} 9.
O-O (9. d3 Ne7 10. O-O {and}) 9... Ne7 {transpose to the 5.e3 non-d4 lines.})
5... g6 6. d3 (6. e3 Bg7 7. Nge2 e4 $11 {[%csl Rd3][%cal Gc6e5]}) 6... Bg7 7.
Nf3 {the only independent try that makes sense. We continue in the typical
fashion with} O-O 8. O-O d6 9. Rb1 {stepping out of the pin.} (9. b4 {would
have been ideal, but after} e4 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Gg7a1] Black can exploit the
pin.} 10. Ne1 d5 $11) 9... h6 $1 {[%cal Gg6g5] intending to gain space with g5.
} 10. b4 g5 {[%csl Ge5,Gf5,Gg5][%cal Gf5f4,Rg5g4,Rh6h5] we have a massive pawn
center. We keep ideas of f4/g4-h5.} 11. b5 {White continues with expansion on
the queenside. An important plan which you should is to meet} Ne7 12. Nd2 g4
13. Nb3 {[%cal Gc4c5] with} c5 $132 {[%cal Gd8e8,Ge8g6,Gh6h5] shutting down
play on the queenside. You are now all set to play Qe8-g6-h5.} *

