{[%evp 0,22,11,-11,-11,-20,-23,-31,48,24,66,-26,5,-6,8,-40,-39,-46,-53,-52,-25,
-15,-15,-25,-23] We are done with the main lines of the Fianchetto English. We
now move back to 3.Nf3, one of White's important alternatives on move 3.} 1. c4
e5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. Nf3 {White doesn't commit to g3 yet, and keeps some
flexibility. Fortunately, we are not bothered and continue with our typical
plan by pushing} f5 $5 {[%csl Ge5,Gf5]} 4. d4 {the only independent try.} (4.
e3 {transposes to the next chapter.}) (4. g3 Nf6 {transposes to the previous
chapter.}) (4. d3 d6 5. g3 {tranposes to the fianchetto English 5.d3 line.}) (
4. e4 $6 fxe4 5. Nxe4 Nf6 {[%csl Rd4]} 6. Nxf6+ Qxf6 {[%csl Rd4,Ge5][%cal
Gf8c5,Gd7d6,Gc8g4] Black is on the better end of equality.}) 4... e4 $1 {
we continue with the thematic plan of gaining space. We need to know a few
moves here.} 5. Ng5 (5. d5 {allows Black to get a slightly better pawn
structure with} exf3 6. dxc6 fxg2 7. cxd7+ Qxd7 8. Qxd7+ Bxd7 9. Bxg2 c6 $11 {
[%csl Rc4,Re2,Gf5][%cal Gg8f6,Ge8f7,Gd7e6,Gf8b4,Gh8e8] Black is on the better
end of equality}) (5. Bg5 {isn't threatening. We are happy to trade bishops
with} Be7 6. Bxe7 Ncxe7 $11 {[%cal Gg8f6,Gd7d5,Ge7g6] while keeping a slight
spacial advantage.}) (5. Ne5 {White invites a knight trade, to keep a pawn in
the center.} Nxe5 6. dxe5 d6 {we undermine that pawn :)} 7. Bf4 {trying to
maintain the pawn doesn't help too, as after} (7. exd6 Bxd6 $15 {[%csl Ge4,Gf5]
}) 7... Ne7 $1 {[%csl Re5,Rf4][%cal Ge7g6] we are going to win the pawn
nevertheless.} 8. exd6 (8. e3 Ng6 $11) 8... Ng6 9. Be3 Qxd6 $11) (5. Nd2 {
was played by some strong players, but I find this much weaker. We have a very
comfortable game with} Nf6 6. e3 (6. Nb3 $6 d5 $15 {Black managed to convert
in Maghsoodloo-Fedoseev.}) 6... g6 $132 {[%cal Gf8g7,Ge8g8,Gd7d6,Gc6e7,Gg6g5]}
(6... Bb4 $5)) (5. Ng1 Bb4 6. Nh3 {tranposes to the main line}) {this time, we
cannot spend time on fianchettoing the bishop due to d5-Qd4, and thus play}
5... Bb4 {[%csl Ge4,Gf5][%cal Gb4c3,Gg8f6,Gd7d5]} (5... g6 6. d5 $16) 6. d5 {
tried by Dubov. However, this gives the important c5 square} (6. Nh3 {[%cal
Gh3f4] was tried by a few players. However, after} Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 d6 {[%csl Rc3,
Rc4][%cal Gg8f6,Ge8g8,Gb7b6,Gc6a5,Gc8a6,Gd8d7] we have a very easy plan. We
want to target the weak pawn on c4.} 8. Nf4 Nf6 9. e3 Qd7 10. Be2 b6 $11 {
[%cal Gc6a5,Gc7c5,Gc8a6]}) (6. Qb3 $4 Nxd4 $19) 6... Ne5 7. Qb3 Qe7 $1 {
Black is the one on the better end of equality due to the extra space. Some
sample lines-} 8. a3 (8. Bf4 Ng6 9. Bd2 a5 $15 {[%cal Gg8f6,Gg6e5]}) 8... Bc5
$15 9. Na4 $2 Bxf2+ $1 10. Kxf2 e3+ 11. Ke1 (11. Bxe3 Ng4+ $19) 11... Qxg5 $15
*

