{[%evp 0,26,19,-11,-31,-20,-26,-26,40,24,52,53,73,70,61,52,55,18,21,10,-5,-5,
19,-12,0,-7,-6,-3,10]} 1. c4 {In this chapter, we will be covering White's
alternatives on move 3 except 3.Nf3} e5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. e3 {a very smart and
potent move order against our setup.} (3. e4 $6 Bc5 $15 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gg8e7,
Gd7d6,Gf7f5]}) (3. a3 {played by Nakamura, but doesn't have a great
independent value. We should transpose somewhere after} f5) (3. d3 f5 {and now
4.Nf3 transposes to a line which we have already checked, while 4.e3
transposes to one of the lines from this chapter. 4.d3 is covered in the next
chapter.}) 3... f5 $1 {we continue with the typical plan regardless.} 4. d4 (4.
d3 Nf6 5. Nf3 d6 {[%cal Gg7g6,Gf8g7] the bishop is not great on e2, where
we'll continue with the thematic g6-Bg7, while g3 should transpose to lines
which we have already checked.}) (4. Nge2 Nf6 5. d4 {tranposes to 5.Nge2.}) (4.
g3 {should transpose to 5.e3 lines in the fianchetto system.}) 4... Nf6 {
this time we bring out our knight, because of White's ideas of early d4-d5.} 5.
d5 (5. Nf3 {allows us to gain space with} e4 6. Ng5 (6. Nd2 {transposes to the
previous chapter.}) 6... Bb4 {[%cal Gb4c3,Gd7d5] followed by Bxc3-d5, gives a
great position due to the extra space.}) ({dissolving the central tension with
} 5. dxe5 {allows us to centralise our knight with} Nxe5 {after} 6. Nf3 Nxf3+
7. Qxf3 g6 $1 $11 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gf8g7,Gf6e4] followed by Bg7, we have a
great position.}) (5. Nge2 d6 6. g3 g6 7. Bg2 Bg7 8. O-O O-O {transposes to
the fianchetto 5.e3-d4 plans.}) 5... Nb8 $1 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Gb8a6,Ga6c5]
aiming for the weak c5-square.} (5... Ne7 $6 {[%cal Gd7d6] We get a good
position if we are able to play d6 next, but White can start with the strong}
6. Qa4 $1 $16 {stopping d6.}) 6. Nf3 {the most logical response. However,
White has a couple of other decent alternatives.} (6. Bd3 {preparing e4 next.
We therefore start by playing} d6 $1 {[%cal Gg7g6,Gf8g7,Gb8d7,Gd7c5,Ga7a5,
Yf8e7]} 7. Nge2 (7. e4 f4 8. g3 $5 {is interesting. We don't recapture, but
sacrifice the pawn in a thematic fashion with} g6 $1 {after} 9. gxf4 exf4 10.
Nge2 Bg7 11. Nxf4 O-O $44 {[%csl Re1,Rf2,Rf4,Gg8][%cal Gf6g4,Gg7c3,Gb8a6,Ga6c5]
we have the thematic compensation.}) 7... Be7 $1 {since White has played d4-d5,
we don't spend time on g6-Bg7.} 8. O-O O-O 9. f4 $5 {trying to increase
pressure in the center. This is met with the thematic} (9. Rb1 a5 $11 {[%cal
Gb8a6,Ga6c5]}) 9... e4 10. Bc2 {[%cal Ge2d4]} c5 $1 $11 {[%cal Gh7h5,Gf6g4,
Gb8a6,Ga6c7,Rc5d4,Ya7a6,Yb7b5,Gh5h4] with a complicated middlegame ahead.}) (6.
e4 {is also possible. White tries to eliminate some of our space advantage.}
fxe4 7. a3 (7. g4 $6 Bb4 $11 {[%cal Gb4c3]}) (7. Nxe4 {is quite possible, but
we can start with} Bb4+ $1 $11 ({it was also possible to play} 7... Nxe4 8.
Qh5+ g6 9. Qxe5+ {where it seems like White is winning, but we have a
perpetual after} Qe7 10. Qxh8 Qb4+ $11)) 7... d6 $1 {[%cal Gc8f5]} 8. Nge2 {
[%cal Ge2g3] White stops our plan of defending e4 with Bf5. therefore, we
prioritise development with} Be7 9. Ng3 O-O 10. Ngxe4 ({delaying Ne4 was also
possible.} 10. Be2 {however, this is met with the thematic} a5 $1 11. O-O Bd7 {
[%cal Gd7e8,Ge8g6,Ya5a4] with equal play. A sample line-} 12. Be3 Be8 13. Ncxe4
Nxe4 14. Nxe4 Bg6 15. Bd3 Nd7 $11 {[%cal Gd8e8,Gd7f6]}) 10... Nxe4 11. Nxe4 Bf5
12. Bd3 Nd7 $11 {[%cal Gd8e8,Ge8g6] with a very healthy position on the board.}
) 6... d6 7. Be2 Be7 {as usual, we play Be7 for early d5 lines.} 8. Rb1 {
the most threatening move practically.} (8. b4 $6 a5 9. b5 Nbd7 $11 {[%csl Gc5]
[%cal Gd7c5]}) (8. O-O {gives us time to play} a5 9. a3 Nbd7 10. b3 Nc5 $11 {
[%csl Gd6,Ge5,Gf5]}) 8... a5 9. a3 O-O 10. b4 Nbd7 $1 {[%cal Gf6e4] preparing
Ne4 Nxe4 fxe4 Nd2 Nf6.} 11. Nd2 {this stops Ne4, but the knight is weaker here.
} (11. O-O Ne4 $1 12. Nxe4 fxe4 13. Nd2 Nf6 $15 {[%cal Gd8e8,Gd8g6] gives us
good attacking prospects on the kingside.}) (11. Qc2 {doesn't stop us from
playing} Ne4 {[%cal Ge4c3] as after} 12. Nxe4 fxe4 13. Qxe4 {we have the
stunning} (13. Nd2 Nf6 $15 {[%cal Gc8f5,Gd8e8,Ge8g6]}) 13... Nc5 $17 {[%cal
Gc8f5]}) 11... Nb6 $1 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Gc8d7,Gb6a4,Gd8e8,Yc7c6] keeping an eye
on c4/a4.} 12. O-O Bd7 13. Qc2 Qe8 $11 {[%cal Gf5f4,Yf6e4,Ya5b4,Yb6a4,Ge8g6]
with a sharp middlegame.} *

